{"title_page": "Afoa Moega Lutu", "text_new": "[[File:AfoaMLutu.jpg|thumb|''HC Afoafouvale Leulumoega S. Lutu'']]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox politician\n|name        = Afoa Moega Lutu\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|2|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Leulumoega]], [[Samoa]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education   = [[Truman State University]]<br>[[University of Hawai\u02bbi at M\u0101noa|University of Hawaii, Manoa]]<br>{{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Valparaiso University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n'''Afoafouvale Leulumoegafou Su\u2019esu\u2019e Lutu''' (born February 24, 1947) is an [[American Samoa]]n politician and lawyer.<ref name=\"afoavelega\">{{cite news|title=About Afoa Biography |url=http://www.afoavelega08.com/index.php?/about/about-afoa/ |work=Afoa and Velega official campaign site |accessdate=19 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029214814/http://www.afoavelega08.com/index.php?%2Fabout%2Fabout-afoa%2F |archivedate=October 29, 2008 }}</ref> Lutu has served as the former [[Attorney General of American Samoa]] in two different administrations.<ref name=pm2>{{cite news|title=People Briefs |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2004/05/01/people-briefs |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] |date=May 1, 2004 |accessdate=19 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121152109/http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2004/05/01/people-briefs |archivedate=November 21, 2008 }}</ref> He is also a former senator from the district of [[Maoputasi County|Maoputasi]], serving the villages of [[Fagatogo]], [[Utulei]] and [[Faga'alu]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = AG Afoa will leave office|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/77381|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref>  He is the current holder of the Afoafouvale title.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nAfoa Moega Lutu was born on February 24, 1947, to [[The Reverend|Rev.]] Su\u2019esu\u2019e Solofa Lutu and Vaitu'utu'u P\u0101tu Leota Leulua'iali'i Lutu.<ref name=afoavelega/> He is the fourth of twelve children in his family.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu's parents taught at the theological school at the [[Ekalesia Fa' apotopotoga Kerisinao I Samoa|Ekalesia Fa'apotopotoga Kerisinao i Samoa]] (Congregational Christian Church in Samoa) in what was then known as [[Western Samoa]], now the independent nation of [[Samoa]].<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu's family moved back to [[American Samoa]] when he was less than a year old and settled in the village of [[Amanave]], where his parents worked as Christian [[Minister (Christianity)|ministers]].<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nHis siblings include six brothers and four sisters: Fa'alele Su'esu'e (dec.), [https://www.greenhillsmortuary.com/obituaries/Faatasiga-Pele/#!/Obituary Faatasiga] Su'esu'e Asuega (dec.), Faaauuga Field Su'esu'e Achica (dec.), Sa'u Taeletoto Smith Lutu (dec.), Silautiti Su'esu'e, Rev. Su'esu'e Su'esu'e (dec.), Matuaifaleese Su'esu'e Lutu Ia, [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/186982518 Omaha] Su'esu'e (dec.), Tavita Su'esu'e and Tiresa Su'esu'e Paogofie.\n\n=== Education ===\nLutu originally attended St. Theresa Elementary School in [[Leone, American Samoa]]. However, his parents moved again to the towns of [[Fagatogo]] and [[Utulei]] by the time he was six years old to live with extended family.<ref name=\"afoavelega\" /> He was admitted to [[Feleti Barstow Public Library|Feleti]] Memorial Barstow Foundation Demonstration School for [[first grade]].<ref name=\"afoavelega\" />\n\nHe became [[salutatorian]] of his eighth grade class upon graduating from the school.  Lutu next entered [[American Samoa High School]]. While in high school, his parents relocated to the village of [[Lauli'i, American Samoa|Lauli'i]], east of [[Pago Pago Harbor]], to work as ministers in the village. He resided with his grandparents, Rev. Su\u2019esu\u2019e and Sola, in [[Utulei]] during the school week, and traveled to see his parents on the weekend.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu graduated as [[student body president]] from high school in 1965.<ref name=afoavelega/> Following his graduation, Lutu was one of four American Samoa students chosen for a [[cultural exchange]] program in the United States. Lutu moved to [[Spirit Lake, Iowa]], to attend an extra year of high school as part of the cultural exchange.  While in Iowa, he stayed at the home of Berkley and Elinor Bedell and their family.<ref name=afoavelega/> [[Berkley Bedell]], Iowan businessman, was later elected as a [[United States Congressman]] (1975\u20131987).\n\nLutu attended [[Northeast Missouri State University]], now known as [[Truman State University]], on a full American Samoa Government scholarship. Lutu met his future wife while at Northeast Missouri, Etenauga Alvina Lam Yuen. Etenauga, whose parents were Pastor Tini Inu Lam Yuen and Tululautu Fueainaula Tagaloa Lam Yuen, was also from a large Samoan family of 10 siblings.\n\nHe transferred to [[University of Hawaii at Manoa|University of Hawai`i at M\u0101noa]] after two years in [[Missouri]] to be closer to his parents, who were working as ministers for the Samoa congregational church in [[N\u0101n\u0101kuli, Hawai'i]], at the time.<ref name=afoavelega/> He graduated from the University of Hawai`i at M\u0101noa in 1968 with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]] and a minor in [[prelaw]].<ref name=afoavelega/> His wife, Etenauga, received her bachelor's degree in [[nursing]] from [[Walla Walla College]], now [[Walla Walla University]].<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu enrolled in the [[Valparaiso University|Valparaiso University School of Law]] with another American Samoa Government scholarship.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu and Etenauga married in [[Lynwood, California]], in 1972.<ref name=afoavelega/> The couple relocated to [[Valparaiso, Indiana]], where Lutu completed his [[Juris Doctorate]] degree.<ref name=afoavelega/> Their first child, Christinna Sola, was born in Indiana in 1973. The couple moved to Hawaii following Lutu's completion of [[law school]].\n\nThe couple had several more children, including Alvina Lore; Faauuga Hannacho in 1977; Elinor Matuaifaleese in 1980; Kimberly Malaeimi in 1982; and Florence-Emma Le\u2019ala in 1983.<ref name=afoavelega/> They also have four sons, Justin Fouvale (1980), Joshua Simanuali\u2019i (1984), Berkley LeAloalii (1989) and Bedell-Macready Tamaalemalo (1995).\n\nIn 1989, the four ''Afoafouvale''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/6822650/massive-family-reunion-for-samoan-high-chief|title=Massive Family Reunion for Samoan High Chief|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> clans of American Samoa, namely ''Lo'i'', ''Pua'a'', ''Taeletoto'', and ''Tualima'', bestowed the title of ''Afoafouvale'' to him.  He was formally granted in a traditional ceremony in 1990 at the Afoa family land, ''Asila''.<ref name=afoavelega/> This marked the first time the title of ''Afoafouvale'' since the mid 1970s.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\n==Career==\nThe family returned to American Samoa in 1975 where Lutu worked as an [[Lawyer|attorney-at-law, until he retired from private practice in 2012]].<ref name=afoavelega/> They eventually settled in [[Taputimu|Taputimu, American Samoa]].\n\nLutu was appointed [[Attorney General of American Samoa]] by Governor [[A. P. Lutali]] after he was elected governor in 1985. He represented American Samoa and the Lutali administration at the early [[South Pacific Tuna Treaty]] negotiations.<ref name=afoavelega/> As attorney general, Lutu also successfully defended challenges to the traditional Samoan [[communal land]] system before [[United States federal courts]] and the [[United States Supreme Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/637/1398/2342760/|title=Corporation of the Presiding Bishop v. Hodel, 637 F. Supp. 1398 (D.D.C. 1986)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nHe next became the special [[legal counsel]] for the President of the [[American Samoa Senate]] from 1998 until 1992.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu was elected to the [[American Samoa House of Representatives]] for Maoputasi District No. 7 in 1992.<ref name=afoavelega/> He spent two terms, a total of four years, in the House, before leaving his seat to become legal counsel to the American Samoa House of Representatives from 1996 until 1997.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu next served as the head of the Legislative Reference Bureau from 1997 until 2004.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nIn 2012, Lutu was again appointed attorney general during the Lolo Moliga administration.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Afoa at AG's post for second time|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/72465|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref> He was the first appointed cabinet member for the new administration.\n\nIn 2013, he stepped down as attorney general to serve his district of Maoputasi No. 7 as senator at the request of HC Tiumalu Telesia Scanlan, representing the villages of Fagatogo, Utulei and Faga'alu.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Am. Samoa Attorney General's Term  Comes To An End \u2013 January 2, 2014|url = http://pidp.org/pireport/2014/January/01-02-05.htm|website = Pacific Islands Report|accessdate = 14 October 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085002/http://pidp.org/pireport/2014/January/01-02-05.htm|archive-date = March 4, 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n===Political ambitions===\nIn 1990 Lutu ran for the American Samoa [[Delegate (House of Representatives)|Delegate]]s in the United States House of Representatives, but was defeated by [[Eni Faleomavaega]].<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu campaigned as the [[running mate]] for [[Lieutenant Governor of American Samoa]] with [[American Samoa Senate|Senator]] [[Lealaifuaneva Peter Reid]] for Governor during the 1996 and 2000 American Samoan gubernatorial elections.<ref name=pm2/> However, Reid and Lutu lost both elections. They were defeated by former governor [[Tauese Sunia]] and then Lt. Governor Tulafono in both 1996 and 2000.<ref name=pm2/>\n\nIn 2004 Lutu ran for Governor of American Samoa in 2004 with [[Taeaoafua]] Dr. [[Meki Solomona]] as his running mate.<ref name=pm2/> The two faced incumbent Governor [[Togiola Tulafono]] and Lt. Governor [[Ipulasi Aitofele Sunia]] in the 2004 general election. However, Tulafono defeated Lutu in the second round [[runoff election]]. Tulafono earned 56 percent of the vote while Lutu garnered 44 percent.<ref name=pm1>{{cite news\n |title=Togiola Reelected Governor \n |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/news/2004/11/18/american-samoa-togiola-reelected-governor \n |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] \n |date=November 18, 2004 \n |accessdate=19 October 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Lutu ran again for the gubernatorial seat for American Samoa with now Senator Velega Savali.  They did not make the run-off election and endorsed the Togiola Tulafono/Aitofele Sunia team during the final election, which they won beating the Utu Abe Malae/Sao Nua team.\n\nIn 2012 Lutu made a final bid for the gubernatorial seat with teammate Le'i Sonny Thompson.<ref>{{Cite web|title = AFOA AND LE&#039;I OFFICIALLY ENTER 2012 GUBERNATORIAL RACE|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/3212|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref> They were unable to meet the needed votes for the run-off election.\n\n===2008 Gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2008}}\n\nAfoa Moega Lutu once again decided to challenge [[Togiola Tulafono|Gov. Togiola Tulafono]] for his office in the [[American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2008|2008 gubernatorial election]].<ref name=pm3>{{cite news|first=Fili |last=Sagapolutele |title=Afoa Criticizes Government's 'Damaged Reputation' |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/news/2008/05/20/afoa-criticizes-governments-damaged-reputation |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=19 October 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Lutu's running mate for Lieutenant Governor is [[Velega Savali]], a former American Samoan Treasurer.<ref name=pm3/>\n\nLutu and Savali launched their campaign for Governor at a kick-off campaign rally at the Tradewinds Hotel on May 17, 2008.<ref name=pm3/> Approximately 700 people attended the rally.<ref name=pm3/> Lutu promised to run on issues such as transparency and improving the territory's public education system.<ref name=pm3/>\n\nThe gubernatorial election took place on November 4, 2008, and Tulafono was re-elected.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.facebook.com/afoa.lutu.9\n*''Official 2008 campaign websites''\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20081016145139/http://www.afoavelega08.com/ Afoa and Velega for Governor and Lt. Governor], Nonpartisan candidates\n***[https://www.myspace.com/afoa_velega2008 Afoa and Velega Official Myspace page]\n***[http://www.bebo.com/Afoa_Velega Afoa and Velega Official Bebo page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Reid (American Samoan politician)|Peter Reid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of governors of American Samoa|Governor of American Samoa]]|years=[[United States gubernatorial elections, 2004|2004]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Utu Abe Malae]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Utu Abe Malae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of governors of American Samoa|Governor of American Samoa]]|years=[[American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2012|2012]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tuika Tuika]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lutu, Afoa Moega}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:American Samoan Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:American Samoan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Samoa House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People from A'ana]]\n[[Category:Truman State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii alumni]]\n[[Category:Valparaiso University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:AfoaMLutu.jpg|thumb|''HC Afoafouvale Leulumoega S. Lutu'']]\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox politician\n|name        = Afoa Moega Lutu\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1947|2|24}}\n|birth_place = [[Leulumoega]], [[Samoa]]\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|education   = [[Truman State University]]<br>[[University of Hawai\u02bbi at M\u0101noa|University of Hawaii, Manoa]]<br>{{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Valparaiso University]] {{small|([[Juris Doctor|JD]])}}\n}}\n'''Afoafouvale Leulumoegafou Su\u2019esu\u2019e Lutu''' (born February 24, 1947) is an [[American Samoa]]n politician and lawyer.<ref name=\"afoavelega\">{{cite news|title=About Afoa Biography |url=http://www.afoavelega08.com/index.php?/about/about-afoa/ |work=Afoa and Velega official campaign site |accessdate=19 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029214814/http://www.afoavelega08.com/index.php?%2Fabout%2Fabout-afoa%2F |archivedate=October 29, 2008 }}</ref> Lutu has served as the former [[Attorney General of American Samoa]] in two different administrations.<ref name=pm2>{{cite news|title=People Briefs |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2004/05/01/people-briefs |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] |date=May 1, 2004 |accessdate=19 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081121152109/http://www.pacificmagazine.net/issue/2004/05/01/people-briefs |archivedate=November 21, 2008 }}</ref> He is also a former senator from the district of [[Maoputasi County|Maoputasi]], serving the villages of [[Fagatogo]], [[Utulei]] and [[Faga'alu]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = AG Afoa will leave office|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/77381|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref>  He is the current holder of the Afoafouvale title.\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nAfoa Moega Lutu was born on February 24, 1947, to [[The Reverend|Rev.]] Su\u2019esu\u2019e Solofa Lutu and Vaitu'utu'u P\u0101tu Leota Leulua'iali'i Lutu.<ref name=afoavelega/> He is the fourth of twelve children in his family.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu's parents taught at the theological school at the [[Ekalesia Fa' apotopotoga Kerisinao I Samoa|Ekalesia Fa'apotopotoga Kerisinao i Samoa]] (Congregational Christian Church in Samoa) in what was then known as [[Western Samoa]], now the independent nation of [[Samoa]].<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu's family moved back to [[American Samoa]] when he was less than a year old and settled in the village of [[Amanave]], where his parents worked as Christian [[Minister (Christianity)|ministers]].<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nHis siblings include six brothers and four sisters: Fa'alele Su'esu'e (dec.), [https://www.greenhillsmortuary.com/obituaries/Faatasiga-Pele/#!/Obituary Faatasiga] Su'esu'e Asuega (dec.), Faaauuga Field Su'esu'e Achica (dec.), Sa'u Taeletoto Smith Lutu (dec.), Silautiti Su'esu'e, Rev. Su'esu'e Su'esu'e (dec.), Matuaifaleese Su'esu'e Lutu Ia, [https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/186982518 Omaha] Su'esu'e (dec.), Tavita Su'esu'e and Tiresa Su'esu'e Paogofie.\n\n=== Education ===\nLutu originally attended St. Theresa Elementary School in [[Leone, American Samoa]]. However, his parents moved again to the towns of [[Fagatogo]] and [[Utulei]] by the time he was six years old to live with extended family.<ref name=\"afoavelega\" /> He was admitted to [[Feleti Barstow Public Library|Feleti]] Memorial Barstow Foundation Demonstration School for [[first grade]].<ref name=\"afoavelega\" />\n\nHe became [[salutatorian]] of his eighth grade class upon graduating from the school.  Lutu next entered [[American Samoa High School]]. While in high school, his parents relocated to the village of [[Lauli'i, American Samoa|Lauli'i]], east of [[Pago Pago Harbor]], to work as ministers in the village. He resided with his grandparents, Rev. Su\u2019esu\u2019e and Sola, in [[Utulei]] during the school week, and traveled to see his parents on the weekend.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu graduated as [[student body president]] from high school in 1965.<ref name=afoavelega/> Following his graduation, Lutu was one of four American Samoa students chosen for a [[cultural exchange]] program in the United States. Lutu moved to [[Spirit Lake, Iowa]], to attend an extra year of high school as part of the cultural exchange.  While in Iowa, he stayed at the home of Berkley and Elinor Bedell and their family.<ref name=afoavelega/> [[Berkley Bedell]], Iowan businessman, was later elected as a [[United States Congressman]] (1975\u20131987).\n\nLutu attended [[Northeast Missouri State University]], now known as [[Truman State University]], on a full American Samoa Government scholarship. Lutu met his future wife while at Northeast Missouri, Etenauga Alvina Lam Yuen. Etenauga, whose parents were Pastor Tini Inu Lam Yuen and Tululautu Fueainaula Tagaloa Lam Yuen, was also from a large American Samoan family of 10 siblings.\n\nHe transferred to [[University of Hawaii at Manoa|University of Hawai`i at M\u0101noa]] after two years in [[Missouri]] to be closer to his parents, who were working as ministers for the Samoa congregational church in [[N\u0101n\u0101kuli, Hawai'i]], at the time.<ref name=afoavelega/> He graduated from the University of Hawai`i at M\u0101noa in 1968 with a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[political science]] and a minor in [[prelaw]].<ref name=afoavelega/> His wife, Etenauga, received her bachelor's degree in [[nursing]] from [[Walla Walla College]], now [[Walla Walla University]].<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu enrolled in the [[Valparaiso University|Valparaiso University School of Law]] with another American Samoa Government scholarship.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu and Etenauga married in [[Lynwood, California]], in 1972.<ref name=afoavelega/> The couple relocated to [[Valparaiso, Indiana]], where Lutu completed his [[Juris Doctorate]] degree.<ref name=afoavelega/> Their first child, Christinna Sola, was born in Indiana in 1973. The couple moved to Hawaii following Lutu's completion of [[law school]].\n\nThe couple had several more children, including Alvina Lore in 1976; Faauuga Hannacho in 1977; Elinor Matuaifaleese in 1980; Kimberly Malaeimi in 1982; and Florence-Emma Le\u2019ala in 1983.<ref name=afoavelega/> They also have four sons, Justin Fouvale (1980), Joshua Simanuali\u2019i (1984), Berkley LeAloalii (1989) and Bedell-Macready Tamaalemalo (1995).\n\nIn 1989, the Afoafouvale<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/6822650/massive-family-reunion-for-samoan-high-chief|title=Massive Family Reunion for Samoan High Chief|website=hawaiinewsnow.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> clans of American Samoa bestowed the title of ''Afoafouvale'' to him and was formally granted in a traditional ceremony in 1990.<ref name=afoavelega/> This marked the first time anyone held the title of ''Afoafouvale'' since the mid 1970s.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\n==Career==\nThe family returned to American Samoa in 1975 where Lutu worked as an [[Lawyer|attorney-at-law, until he retired from private practice in 2012]].<ref name=afoavelega/> They eventually settled in [[Taputimu|Taputimu, American Samoa]].\n\nLutu was appointed [[Attorney General of American Samoa]] by Governor [[A. P. Lutali]] after he was elected governor in 1985. He represented American Samoa and the Lutali administration at the early [[South Pacific Tuna Treaty]] negotiations.<ref name=afoavelega/> As attorney general, Lutu also successfully defended challenges to the traditional Samoan [[communal land]] system before [[United States federal courts]] and the [[United States Supreme Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/637/1398/2342760/|title=Corporation of the Presiding Bishop v. Hodel, 637 F. Supp. 1398 (D.D.C. 1986)|website=Justia Law|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nHe next became the special [[legal counsel]] for the President of the [[American Samoa Senate]] from 1998 until 1992.<ref name=afoavelega/> Lutu was elected to the [[American Samoa House of Representatives]] for Maoputasi District No. 7 in 1992.<ref name=afoavelega/> He spent two terms, a total of four years, in the House, before leaving his seat to become legal counsel to the American Samoa House of Representatives from 1996 until 1997.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu next served as the head of the Legislative Reference Bureau from 1997 until 2004.<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nIn 2012, Lutu was again appointed attorney general during the Lolo Moliga administration.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Afoa at AG's post for second time|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/72465|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref> He was the first appointed cabinet member for the new administration.\n\nIn 2013, he stepped down as attorney general to serve his district of Maoputasi No. 7 as senator at the request of HC Tiumalu Telesia Scanlan, representing the villages of Fagatogo, Utulei and Faga'alu.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Am. Samoa Attorney General's Term  Comes To An End \u2013 January 2, 2014|url = http://pidp.org/pireport/2014/January/01-02-05.htm|website = Pacific Islands Report|accessdate = 14 October 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304085002/http://pidp.org/pireport/2014/January/01-02-05.htm|archive-date = March 4, 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\n===Political ambitions===\nIn 1990 Lutu ran for the American Samoa [[Delegate (House of Representatives)|Delegate]]s in the United States House of Representatives, but was defeated by [[Eni Faleomavaega]].<ref name=afoavelega/>\n\nLutu campaigned as the [[running mate]] for [[Lieutenant Governor of American Samoa]] with [[American Samoa Senate|Senator]] [[Lealaifuaneva Peter Reid]] for Governor during the 1996 and 2000 American Samoan gubernatorial elections.<ref name=pm2/> However, Reid and Lutu lost both elections. They were defeated by former governor [[Tauese Sunia]] and then Lt. Governor Tulafono in both 1996 and 2000.<ref name=pm2/>\n\nIn 2004 Lutu ran for Governor of American Samoa in 2004 with [[Taeaoafua]] Dr. [[Meki Solomona]] as his running mate.<ref name=pm2/> The two faced incumbent Governor [[Togiola Tulafono]] and Lt. Governor [[Ipulasi Aitofele Sunia]] in the 2004 general election. However, Tulafono defeated Lutu in the second round [[runoff election]]. Tulafono earned 56 percent of the vote while Lutu garnered 44 percent.<ref name=pm1>{{cite news\n |title=Togiola Reelected Governor \n |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/news/2004/11/18/american-samoa-togiola-reelected-governor \n |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] \n |date=November 18, 2004 \n |accessdate=19 October 2008 \n}}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 Lutu ran again for the gubernatorial seat for American Samoa with now Senator Velega Savali.  They did not make the run-off election and endorsed the Togiola Tulafono/Aitofele Sunia team during the final election, which they won beating the Utu Abe Malae/Sao Nua team.\n\nIn 2012 Lutu made a final effort for the gubernatorial seat with teammate Le'i Sonny Thompson.<ref>{{Cite web|title = AFOA AND LE&#039;I OFFICIALLY ENTER 2012 GUBERNATORIAL RACE|url = http://www.samoanews.com/node/3212|website = Samoa News|accessdate = 14 October 2015}}</ref> They were unable to meet the need votes for the run-off election.\n\n===2008 Gubernatorial election===\n{{Main|American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2008}}\n\nAfoa Moega Lutu once again decided to challenge Gov. Togiola Tulafono for his office in the [[American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2008|2008 gubernatorial election]].<ref name=pm3>{{cite news|first=Fili |last=Sagapolutele |title=Afoa Criticizes Government's 'Damaged Reputation' |url=http://www.pacificmagazine.net/news/2008/05/20/afoa-criticizes-governments-damaged-reputation |work=[[Pacific Magazine]] |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=19 October 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Lutu's running mate for Lieutenant Governor is [[Velega Savali]], a former American Samoan Treasurer.<ref name=pm3/>\n\nLutu and Savali launched their campaign for Governor at a kick-off campaign rally at the Tradewinds Hotel on May 17, 2008.<ref name=pm3/> Approximately 700 people attended the rally.<ref name=pm3/> Lutu promised to run on issues such as transparency and improving the territory's public education system.<ref name=pm3/>\n\nThe gubernatorial election took place on November 4, 2008, and Tulafono was re-elected.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.facebook.com/afoa.lutu.9\n*''Official 2008 campaign websites''\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/20081016145139/http://www.afoavelega08.com/ Afoa and Velega for Governor and Lt. Governor], Nonpartisan candidates\n***[https://www.myspace.com/afoa_velega2008 Afoa and Velega Official Myspace page]\n***[http://www.bebo.com/Afoa_Velega Afoa and Velega Official Bebo page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Reid (American Samoan politician)|Peter Reid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of governors of American Samoa|Governor of American Samoa]]|years=[[United States gubernatorial elections, 2004|2004]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Utu Abe Malae]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Utu Abe Malae]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of governors of American Samoa|Governor of American Samoa]]|years=[[American Samoa gubernatorial election, 2012|2012]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tuika Tuika]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lutu, Afoa 